data.message: it has applications in concurrency. Thread.Sleep(n) where n is a specific number is typically used in polling. It puts the thread to sleep for a given number of milliseconds, similar to using delay(n) on the Arduino platform. A more powerful way to utilize threads is to follow the interrupt model and put a thread to sleep and then have it woken up when some status is true.
Okay awesome. Thanks for making the connection to Arduino that really helped me. What does Thread.Sleep(0) do then?
Thread.Sleep(0) is one way to typically cause a switch to a different thread to be processed, one that usually has equal or higher priority
Thanks a lot! I was reading that online, but not fully understanding it until now.

Thread.Sleep() can also be used (and I most frequently see it used) as a synchronization hack. For instance, say you have an asynchronous process that takes ~5 seconds to finish. If you depend on the return of that function, you can stick a Thread.Sleep(10000) in there, so you can semi-guarantee that you have the return value you need before continuing code execution.

This isn't how you *should* do it, but I see a lot of code like this in test environments.

Gursimran, any tips/guides on how to force yourself to do it

Always write the test first. Picking a dead simple library is important, like minitest. Also, try to minimally pass your first tests and then write some more till you cover all branches of code and a good enough variance of values.

If you're pairing, have one person write the test and the other try to maliciously pass it with the dumbest, simplest code. Rinse and repeat, and switch roles over a few hours. For a problem, I'd suggest Conway's Game of Life.

I think it heavily depends on what you're working on. Certain frameworks or projects lend themselves nicely or testing. Working on a nodejs public facing API? Test it. Working on a background service on Android? Probably not worth your time.
In my experience, unit tests don't catch most problems anyways because complex bugs rarely fail because of the I/O of a specific function and more because of complex interactions/race conditions in the overall system.
Programming is an art. Being anal about BDD/TDD turns it into a science and takes all of the fun away. Go move fast, break things, and have fun.

But science is fun! :)

But yeah, it depends on what you're working on. My usual thinking is to consider if it'll be maintained over a long time or if others will need to use it (and if it's actually worth my time), and if so I opt to go with test-driven style.

Thinking about invariants and properties before coding actually frees you up over time, since you can gain confidence about the behavior of individual components and integrate them together with less cognitive load. Also, less stress and easier refactoring. Then you can spike a new feature without worry.

data.message: i don't think i've encountered a blog post that i disagreed with more. at least, one that wasn't intended to be ironic.
I don't agree with everything either but it was an interesting read.
Wait, this isn't an April's Fools joke?!

I actually wrote about this issue a while back taking the opposing side. Its interesting how differently people view the subject of coding.

http://b-lichliter.tumblr.com/post/60900861335/on-coding-and-its-future-in-society

I mostly agree with what he's saying. I think people should be encouraged to try coding, to see if it interests them. Then, they can pursue coding further if they enjoy it. But this blanket "everyone should code" idea isn't helpful. It should be "everyone should try to code." But everyone should try a lot of things.

Also, one of the tenets of this idea is that many people lack a critical understanding of technology. I couldn't agree more. It's frankly dangerous how much people misunderstand and even fear technology. But is learning how to program really the best way to encourage knowledge of technology? Does knowing JavaScript help you understand how the Internet works? I believe more general knowledge of technologies people use in everyday life is far more important.

i agree that perhaps 'everyone should try to code' is a better general message. but a slogan like 'yeah you should give it a shot but if it doesn't work out for you it's okay' probably isn't as enticing for getting more americans into STEM fields :P and i also think it is alarming how many people are mystified by technology and how many friends and family mistakenly think i'm some ultra super genius for studying computer science. however, i fail to see how say, knowing how the internet works, is something that a non-technical person would even need to understand, even though everyone uses the internet all the time. 

to me, the whole movement of encouraging people to learn an hour+ of programming (though my perspective is that this whole learn-to-code! campaign is geared at/intended to benefit children, rather than adults) is more about demystifying computer science and teaching individuals a new way to think and problem-solve.

Part of this problem with people mystified by tech will disappear over time as the millennials and digital natives get older (although there will be something new we wont understand later in life im sure!)

and I 100% agree about " demystifying computer science and teaching individuals a new way to think and problem-solve." being the main goal of this coding initiative.

4 years working in IT taught me that there are many millennials that are just as bad at technology as their parents and grandparents. So we definitely need initiatives to help curb this issue, for the foreseeable future.

I feel like the article was right about problem solving - the key thing people should be learning is how to solve issues.  The biggest issue is that people get intimidated by technology.  Coding itself really isn't a key skill, but what becoming a programmer does is it really makes you think about how to approach an issue - what resources you have, and how to solve a conceptual issue with a discreet solution. Some more emphasis on not being scared about technology would be extremely helpful - it's ridiculous how intimidated people get about their computers when it doesn't work, and just complain and do nothing about it.

I have to +1 everything Josiah has said. The main issue is people's ineptitude with and fear of technology, regardless of age. I have seen *many* of my peers struggle with technology in the silliest ways, and I have also seen many (though not quite as many) baby boomers go nuts with technology.

Are you specifically interested in the single threaded use case (e.g. a browser thread)?

Not specifically; I'm trying to learn it in a more abstract and language agnostic way.

So I can then ... do concurrency in a single browser thread using JS callbacks and deferred promises or ... weigh the pros on cons of using Twisted/Tornado vs. coroutines + gevent in python

Basically anything with an emphasis on 'proper' event driven programming.
Distributed Systems deals with event driven programming a fair amount. That's the closest class I've taken to what you're looking for, but I didn't take them all.

So the basic list of all the weird control structures like coroutines, continuations, async blocks, go blocks, iterator blocks, etc is that they move away from the idea that programming is really about stack machines. Roughly, it amounts to rewriting subsets of the program into continuation-passing style where alternative stacks of execution are stored around in memory.

It's common to write something like this with callbacks:

(do-something-that-takes-a-long-time (lambda (result) (do-the-next-thing result)))

which can be kind of hard to follow. Instead, you'd rather write something like:

(do-the-next-thing (this-may-take-a-while (do-something-that-takes-a-long-time)))

basically, this-may-take-a-while is the operation that says "i'm done for now. call me later when you have the information i want". the 'this-may-take-a-while' operator is equivalent to 'yield', 'await', and go's blocking 'give me a value from a channel' operator.

So (if you have them) you should probably use alternative control structures in most cases where you're not doing the usual operations with higher-order functions (mapping, reducing, blah blah blah).

But if you want a survey, you'll want to check out:

- c# and pythons iterator and generator blocks 
- rackets coroutines and continuations (these are undoubtedly implemented in a different way that jiggles with the real stack since they don't require annotations and all of the operators are first class procedures instead of special forms or syntax)
- c#s async/await
- ruby's fibers
- stackless python
- goroutines in go and go blocks in clojure
- Paul Graham's fake continuations in Common Lisp (in the book On Lisp)

Lisp: 1958

Symbolic Manipulation Program (SMP, influenced by Macsyma): 1979

The docs makes it sound as though the features mentioned were only recently introduced, yet the pages it links to say at the bottom that the features (the docs) were introduced in 1988. Assuming that this is meant to illustrate the failure that is healthcare.gov, I am rather disappointed to see this image continue circulating. As seen here (https://docs.google.com/spreadsheet/ccc?key=0Aqe2P9sYhZ2ndElxbjVTcnV2bHFOWmUwSkt2bjZLdVE&usp=drive_web#gid=5), exactly one source is cited for the 500 million lines of code figure: a NYT article from Oct. 21. So, we go to this NYT article (http://www.nytimes.com/2013/10/21/us/insurance-site-seen-needing-weeks-to-fix.html?pagewanted=all&_r=1&) and see that the source of this figure is "one specialist." The claim sounds dubious at best.

Frankly, I think that this infographic gives undeserved credit to the people involved in the project. I would be impressed if they managed to write that much code in such a short timespan, regardless of the quality of the code. We're talking 50M lines in less than 4 years. I find it hard to believe that more code was produced in 4 years for this project than the combined codebase of all Debian packages (37,500 packages currently) over the past...20 years or so?

While we can't know for certain the SLOC count of healthcare.gov, the following give some things to consider:

http://skeptics.stackexchange.com/questions/18364/does-healthcare-gov-contain-500-million-lines-of-code/18382#18382

http://www.slate.com/articles/technology/bitwise/2013/10/healthcare_gov_problems_what_5_million_lines_of_code_really_means.html

Even excluding the seemingly grossly estimated figure for healthcare.gov, I'm not sure the figure is all that insightful. What is a "line of code"? Do comments count? Whitespace? Third-party libraries? Is SLOC count even a meaningful metric?

Regardless, it is fun to look at, and I suppose it's interesting to see how codebases have grown over time, but it's easy to just accept the numbers without question; even more so for healthcare.gov, for which many people already harbor a certain amount of disdain.

It also makes no sense that the average high end car has 10x the lines of code as the Volt. The only way to get such ridiculous numbers is to do something like
((software image size  / bytes per char / chars per line of code) * temperature of the air outside * number of calories eaten that day)^2 and leave it at that.

We'll supply the food, fun diversions, prizes, and some expert guidance in the form of our engineers. You bring your laptop, appetite, skills and ideas.

The winning team will get the chance to compete against teams from other Hackathons both domestically and internationally at the Hackathon Finals and be judged by our executives- held at Facebook HQ in Menlo Park, California in November!

*Note: You must be an enrolled university student to attend.

FAQ:

Q: Will transportation be provided?
A: YES! We will provide a bus to and from the event from some Illinois universities. Stay tuned for details...

Q: What type of things should we build?
A: The world is your oyster- think of something that annoyed you today. Harness that and build your next hack. Disrupting the current industry is highly encouraged, these are the best ideas! 

Q: Does our project have to relate to Facebook?
A: Not at all. But our engineers are best equipped to answer any FB related questions.

Q: Do I have to be on a team? What if I don’t have one?
A: No, but working in teams will typically allow you to get more done in the limited amount of time you'll have. If you don't have a team on the day of, we can help you find or create one.

Q: Can I have a team of more than 4 people?
A: Only four people will be flown out to California for the Hackathon Finals. You can have more than four at your school Hackathon but you’ll only get four airplane tickets.

Q: What language or platform can I use?
A: The choice is yours! As long as you are confident that you can come up with a working prototype by the end of the hackathon, you should be fine.

Q: Will food be provided?
A: It wouldn’t be a Facebook hackathon without food, and lots of it! We’ll also have plenty of caffeine drinks to keep the energy high all night long. 

Q: What should I bring?
A: You should bring yourself, great ideas and a laptop. Pillows, blankets, deodorant and a toothbrush are strongly recommended but optional. 

Q: Who owns the code after we're done?
A: You do! Facebook does not own any of your code. Feel free to open source your code, expand on it, etc. This is a great opportunity to make use of advice from industry experts!

Q: Is it okay to work on a project we've created in the past?
A: Yes, feel free to use an existing project as a starting point, and create something new out of it. You can also come armed with pieces of code you might have worked on in the past and use it to get your project off the ground faster. Be sure to show one of our engineers the work you’ve already completed in the beginning, as we’ll judge your product based on the progress you make during the event.

data.message: I typed out a four paragraph rant and then decided to just state that I would like to rant about this subject without actually doing it.
In one or two unsupported sentences, what do you feel strongly?

Most of the criticisms of callbacks come from people who don't try to use any sort of callback control flow library.

Then, yes, they suck. But you're ignorant if you do that. That's like trying to pound a nail into a board with your hand and exclaiming "Nails are the worst invention EVER!". "Have you... have you considered a hammer?"

I see.  I think that in this case that analogy is not really appropriate.  If you are always forced to write libraries, wrappers, macros and abstractions around the thing, than its semantics are bad and aren't an adequate tool of expression.

Note! That a tool of expression is different from a tool of execution!  Obviously GOTOs make a lot of sense as a tool of execution. Every processor still runs jump commands.  BUT GOTOs do a fantastically bad job as a part of the language that we think of programs in.  So we write abstractions in our language around them to hide them from us.

The same thing is true of callbacks:  absolutely necessary to execute but you also should never be writing them yourself

But you aren't "forced to write libraries, wrapper, macros and abstractions" around callbacks. Someone else already did those - they already exist. Even async in C# is just another version of those, as the author freely admits.

I think the main problem is that the title if the article and the first two paragraphs make a very different argument ("callbacks are the devil") than the rest of the article ("C#'s async is my favorite abstraction on callbacks"), and he never tries to justify his "callbacks are the devil" argument.

I think you're missing the point.   Callbacks, like gotos, aren't evil when they are hidden from you.  His point is that they should be hidden under the compiler or a library where you can't see them.   To assume that the author is saying that they're evil _in essence_ is to assume too much

"Callbacks, like gotos, aren't evil when they are hidden from you."

That pre-supposes that callbacks are evil if you have to use them, a point which Miguel never justifies. Given that the author equates first-order functions with callbacks, there's an entire world of functional programmers who would probably have a lot to say to him.

They are a very powerful feature and, yes, they can make things worse if you use them improperly. But simply because someone else uses callbacks wrong doesn't mean that they're bad. That's what makes them fundamentally different from GOTO, where pretty much ANY use was wrong.

I agree that first-order functions shouldn't be bucketed in with callbacks.   My personal opinion is:

GOOD
______
array_map( (b) { return b.a + 2; }, my_array)

BAD
____
array_map( 'func', my_array)

object::func (a) { return self.a + 2; }
If you've ever done kernel work / low-level system programming you realized the complete sham that is "GOTO considered harmful".

Also what if you're using not C# and you don't have a compiler to hide this away for you. You can't just wait around for someone to write it into the compiler, and when they do, they're just going to implement it in the same way anyway.
